node.text:
As adaptive athletes take to the world’s biggest stage, Facebook Groups like Wheelchair Scooterboarding and More continue to redefine the limits of their sport and push each other. Scooterboarder Erik K., adaptive skater Kanya S. and WCMX riders Delmace M. and Nathan R., share their skills and how they play their way. #MoreTogether #WeThe15 

Link in bio for an audio described version of this video.

#NoAwardForThat is a series imagined and created by a community of Black creatives from Hue You Know... for BIPOC in Media Facebook Group. 

Members from the Group created a short film, “A Useful Dream”, exploring the true reward of Black creativity by capturing the power of Black imagination, especially in childhood. “While Black children learn early on that they have to dream beyond their circumstances to find joy, we grow up with the sentiment that the joy we create in these intimate moments cannot be taken from us.” - DaeQuan C. #LiftBlackVoices #MoreTogether

Director: DaeQuan Alexander Collier @daequan
Director of Photography: Ashley Smith @ash_innovator
Editor: Princess Hairston @princessahairston

"To be strong, it comes from the inside out. Our strength is steeped in something greater than ourselves."

Meet Reverend Stacey, founder of Fertility for Colored Girls. In this video, Reverend Stacey addresses the misconceptions and stigmas surrounding Black women and fertility. She also shares her fertility journey along with the importance of education and empowerment surrounding fertility. #LiftBlackVoices

“There are many deaf kids who feel like they cannot play sports… I want them to know they can play at any level.” — Serenity F. 

On the court Serenity plays basketball in a team of five, but off the court, her team, the DeafHoops Facebook Group is four thousand strong. Together, they share advice and help each other be the best ballers they can be, their way. #MoreTogether #WeThe15 

Link in bio for an audio described version of Serenity’s video.

node.accessibility_caption: Adaptive climber Jake S. climbs a rock face using a prosthetic leg. A hand-written quote reads “It might be hard at first and you’ll definitely have to adapt, but don’t give up. Keep pushing yourself. It’s worth it.” SoCal Climbing Facebook Group logo.

node.text:
“DeafHoops helps me to play basketball my way — with determination and fierceness… we play for each other and for the reputation of being a deaf basketball player.” — Serenity F. 

As adaptive athletes shine at the world’s biggest sporting event, basketballers, climbers and surfers from DeafHoops, SoCal Climbing and Coastal Adaptive Sports Facebook Groups share how they stay on their game, push each other and do things their way. #MoreTogether #WeThe15

node.accessibility_caption: Adaptive climber Jake S. climbs a rock face using a prosthetic leg. A hand-written quote reads “It might be hard at first and you’ll definitely have to adapt, but don’t give up. Keep pushing yourself. It’s worth it.” SoCal Climbing Facebook Group logo.

Deaf basketball player Serenity F. holds a basketball on a court. In a smaller image she’s taking a shot. A hand-written quote reads: “Knowing deaf ballers have my back means the world to me.” DeafHoops Facebook Group logo.

Adaptive surfer Ernie J. rides a wave laying on his board grasping two hand grips. A hand-written quote reads “People who sometimes feel like they have no one, have the opportunity to feel like they are a part of something.” Coastal Adaptive Sports Facebook Group logo.
